<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/oklahoma-prisoner-dialed-911-report-escape-183454285.html"><img src="http://l1.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/75lYb9KEQ3Fd27o.IhR3Ow--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3B4b2ZmPTUwO3B5b2ZmPTA7cT04NTt3PTEzMA--/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/ap_webfeeds/4f77fc9596c088203e0f6a706700d459.jpg" width="130" height="86" alt="This undated booking photo provided by the Weatherford Police Department shows Joshua Silverman. Silverman was among eight prisoners in a van when two other inmates had stolen the unattended transport vehicle in an attempted escape. Silverman called 911 to report the escape. (AP Photo/Weatherford Police Department)" align="left" title="This undated booking photo provided by the Weatherford Police Department shows Joshua Silverman. Silverman was among eight prisoners in a van when two other inmates had stolen the unattended transport vehicle in an attempted escape. Silverman called 911 to report the escape. (AP Photo/Weatherford Police Department)" border="0" /></a>TULSA, Okla. (AP) — Prisoner Joshua Silverman passed up a taste of freedom this week and called the police instead.</p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/feds-direct-100m-grants-help-broke-detroit-000259669.html' target="_blank">Feds direct $100M in grants to help broke Detroit</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/feds-direct-100m-grants-help-broke-detroit-000259669.html"><img src="http://l2.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/cMkajzKlyjnuLUfpUzjvVA--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/ap_webfeeds/8f3a2baf7cd187203e0f6a7067004c18.jpg" width="130" height="86" alt="A young man walks in front of a row of abandoned houses in Detroit, Thursday, Sept. 26, 2013. Four of President Barack Obama&#039;s top advisers will converge on Detroit Friday to meet privately with state and local leaders about ways the federal government can help the bankrupt city short of a bailout. The White House said Thursday that top economic adviser Gene Sperling will join U.S. Attorney General Eric Holder, Transportation Secretary Anthony Foxx and HUD Secretary Shaun Donovan in the closed meeting. (AP Photo/Carlos Osorio)" align="left" title="A young man walks in front of a row of abandoned houses in Detroit, Thursday, Sept. 26, 2013. Four of President Barack Obama&#039;s top advisers will converge on Detroit Friday to meet privately with state and local leaders about ways the federal government can help the bankrupt city short of a bailout. The White House said Thursday that top economic adviser Gene Sperling will join U.S. Attorney General Eric Holder, Transportation Secretary Anthony Foxx and HUD Secretary Shaun Donovan in the closed meeting. (AP Photo/Carlos Osorio)" border="0" /></a>DETROIT (AP) — The U.S. government directed more than $100 million in grants Thursday to help bankrupt Detroit tear down vacant buildings and spur job growth, but the help falls far short of the wider bailout some city leaders had sought.</p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/california-solar-policy-costing-utility-customers-report-014907283--finance.html' target="_blank">California solar policy costing all utility customers: report</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/california-solar-policy-costing-utility-customers-report-014907283--finance.html"><img src="http://l1.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/pwrUpLQ_rJmU0n_cJYuG7w--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/Reuters/2013-09-27T014907Z_1_CBRE98Q052500_RTROPTP_2_SOLAR-LOANS.JPG" width="130" height="86" alt="A home with solar panels on its roof is shown in a residential neighborhood in San Marcos" align="left" title="A home with solar panels on its roof is shown in a residential neighborhood in San Marcos" border="0" /></a>By Nichola Groom LOS ANGELES (Reuters) - California&#039;s non-solar homeowners are paying a growing share of maintaining the power grid under a controversial state policy, while ratepayers with solar rooftops are paying less, a report commissioned by the state&#039;s utility regulator said on Thursday. The report, which was issued by the California Public Utilities Commission but performed by an outside research firm, forecast that in 2020, the policy of &quot;net metering&quot; would cost $1.1 billion a year. It will shift about $359 million in costs a year from customers with solar panels to other ratepayers. </p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/elvis-impersonator-wrongly-arrested-sending-ricin-obama-sues-013618294.html' target="_blank">Elvis impersonator wrongly arrested for sending ricin to Obama sues accuser</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/elvis-impersonator-wrongly-arrested-sending-ricin-obama-sues-013618294.html"><img src="http://l2.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/KrL564z8dhxxf2iHKTBKAA--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/Reuters/2013-09-27T013618Z_1_CBRE98Q04GT00_RTROPTP_2_USA-SECURITY.JPG" width="130" height="86" alt="Federal officials stand outside the house of Paul Kevin Curtis while searching for evidence in Corinth" align="left" title="Federal officials stand outside the house of Paul Kevin Curtis while searching for evidence in Corinth" border="0" /></a>By Emily Le Coz JACKSON, Mississippi (Reuters) - An Elvis impersonator from Mississippi falsely accused of sending ricin-tainted letters to President Barack Obama and other officials filed a lawsuit on Wednesday against the man authorities now believe is the real perpetrator. Paul Kevin Curtis, who was arrested and released in April, wants an unspecified amount of money from James Everette Dutschke for defamation of character, emotional distress and financial loss. </p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/justice-department-spent-nearly-5m-drones-212220839--politics.html' target="_blank">Justice Department spent nearly $5M on drones</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/justice-department-spent-nearly-5m-drones-212220839--politics.html"><img src="http://l2.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/zp7ohUuGzO5BcYpXebFQiA--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/ap_webfeeds/56ef56457cb186203e0f6a706700f2c8.jpg" width="130" height="86" alt="FILE - This Jan. 8, 2009 file photo provided by the Mesa County, Colo., Sheriff&#039;s Department shows a small Draganflyer X6 drone during a test flight in Mesa County, Colo., with a Forward Looking Infer Red payload. The FBI has been using drones to support its law enforcement operations since 2006 and has spent more than $3 million on the unmanned aircraft, the Justice Department&#039;s internal watchdog said Thursday, Sept. 26, 2013. (AP Photo/Mesa County Sheriff&#039;s Unmanned Operations Team)" align="left" title="FILE - This Jan. 8, 2009 file photo provided by the Mesa County, Colo., Sheriff&#039;s Department shows a small Draganflyer X6 drone during a test flight in Mesa County, Colo., with a Forward Looking Infer Red payload. The FBI has been using drones to support its law enforcement operations since 2006 and has spent more than $3 million on the unmanned aircraft, the Justice Department&#039;s internal watchdog said Thursday, Sept. 26, 2013. (AP Photo/Mesa County Sheriff&#039;s Unmanned Operations Team)" border="0" /></a>WASHINGTON (AP) — The FBI has been using drones to support its law enforcement operations since 2006 and has spent more than $3 million on the unmanned aircraft, the Justice Department&#039;s internal watchdog said Thursday.</p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/10-things-know-friday-103047600.html' target="_blank">10 Things to Know for Friday</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/10-things-know-friday-103047600.html"><img src="http://l3.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/zyWsP6K3HVADinJoMJFbgg--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/ap_webfeeds/7a1307157c3984203e0f6a7067009911.jpg" width="130" height="86" alt="FILE - In this Saturday, Sept. 21, 2013, file photo, armed police leave after entering the Westgate Mall in Nairobi, Kenya, after gunmen threw grenades and opened fire Saturday, killing at least 22 people in an attack targeting non-Muslims at the upscale mall. First-hand accounts of the chaotic first hours of the four-day siege of Kenya&#039;s posh Westgate Mall are beginning to emerge. First-hand accounts of the chaotic first hours of the four-day siege of Kenya&#039;s posh Westgate Mall are beginning to emerge. (AP Photo/Jonathan Kalan, File)" align="left" title="FILE - In this Saturday, Sept. 21, 2013, file photo, armed police leave after entering the Westgate Mall in Nairobi, Kenya, after gunmen threw grenades and opened fire Saturday, killing at least 22 people in an attack targeting non-Muslims at the upscale mall. First-hand accounts of the chaotic first hours of the four-day siege of Kenya&#039;s posh Westgate Mall are beginning to emerge. First-hand accounts of the chaotic first hours of the four-day siege of Kenya&#039;s posh Westgate Mall are beginning to emerge. (AP Photo/Jonathan Kalan, File)" border="0" /></a>Your daily look at late-breaking news, upcoming events and the stories that will be talked about Friday:</p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/panel-backs-easing-electronic-device-planes-235810322--politics.html' target="_blank">Panel backs easing electronic device use on planes</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/panel-backs-easing-electronic-device-planes-235810322--politics.html"><img src="http://l.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/LsQa037QaJpYisiXjQsWuQ--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/ap_webfeeds/f3c8541696c488203e0f6a706700bd5d.jpg" width="130" height="86" alt="FILE - In this June 18, 2013 file photo, Sen. Claire McCaskill, D-Mo., speaks on Capitol Hill in Washington. Airline passengers may get some relief from restrictions on use of personal electronic devices during takeoffs and landings, but probably not for at least months and maybe longer, industry insiders say. A special advisory committee is expected to deliver recommendations Monday to FAA calling for gate-to-gate use of some devices on some planes. But the soonest FAA is likely to implement new regulations is early 2014. McCaskill says she’ll introduce legislation to force FAA’s hand if the agency doesn’t act swiftly. (AP Photo/Manuel Balce Ceneta, File)" align="left" title="FILE - In this June 18, 2013 file photo, Sen. Claire McCaskill, D-Mo., speaks on Capitol Hill in Washington. Airline passengers may get some relief from restrictions on use of personal electronic devices during takeoffs and landings, but probably not for at least months and maybe longer, industry insiders say. A special advisory committee is expected to deliver recommendations Monday to FAA calling for gate-to-gate use of some devices on some planes. But the soonest FAA is likely to implement new regulations is early 2014. McCaskill says she’ll introduce legislation to force FAA’s hand if the agency doesn’t act swiftly. (AP Photo/Manuel Balce Ceneta, File)" border="0" /></a>WASHINGTON (AP) — A Federal Aviation Administration advisory committee recommended Thursday that airline passengers be allowed to use smartphones, tablets, e-readers and other personal electronic devices during takeoffs and landings, according to industry officials familiar with the committee&#039;s deliberations.</p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/calif-becomes-laboratory-affordable-care-act-233904431.html' target="_blank">Calif. becomes laboratory for Affordable Care Act</a><br />
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) — A national health policy nonprofit on Thursday announced it is making California the focal point of a long-term research project to examine whether the Affordable Care Act lives up to expectations for the uninsured.
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/texas-man-put-death-murder-over-100-debt-001713116--finance.html' target="_blank">Texas man put to death for murder over $100 debt</a><br />
By Brendan O'Brien (Reuters) - A Texas man who stabbed another man to death for failing to pay back a $100 debt to an exotic dancer was executed on Thursday by lethal injection, a state corrections official said. Arturo Diaz was pronounced dead at 6:30 p.m. CT (2330 GMT) in Huntsville, according to Jason Clark, spokesman for the Texas Department of Criminal Justice. It was the 13th execution this year in Texas and the 27th in the United States. "Let's go warden. I'm ready," were his last words, Clark said. 
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/3-transformers-headed-crippled-ny-conn-rail-001757701.html' target="_blank">3 transformers headed to crippled NY, Conn. rail</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/3-transformers-headed-crippled-ny-conn-rail-001757701.html"><img src="http://l2.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/lExshSJ1U79tFBK4ZuHY9w--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/ap_webfeeds/a3dfa1d45df66f203e0f6a7067009998.jpg" width="130" height="86" alt="Pedestrians pass a depopulated New Haven transit line departures board at Grand Central Terminal, Wednesday, Sept. 25, 2013, in New York. Connecticut Gov. Dannel P. Malloy is warning commuters that it could take up to three weeks to fix broken equipment that has snarled service to and from New York City on the nation&#039;s second-largest commuter railroad. (AP Photo/John Minchillo)" align="left" title="Pedestrians pass a depopulated New Haven transit line departures board at Grand Central Terminal, Wednesday, Sept. 25, 2013, in New York. Connecticut Gov. Dannel P. Malloy is warning commuters that it could take up to three weeks to fix broken equipment that has snarled service to and from New York City on the nation&#039;s second-largest commuter railroad. (AP Photo/John Minchillo)" border="0" /></a>NEW YORK (AP) — Officials announced a plan to supply partial power to a heavily trafficked line of the nation&#039;s second largest commuter railroad as tens of thousands of commuters took to the highways and continued to scramble for alternative routes after a power failure disrupted service along the line serving the densely populated Connecticut suburbs and New York City.</p><br clear="all"/>
<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/colo-farmers-arrested-fatal-listeria-outbreak-185524864.html' target="_blank">Colo. farmers arrested in fatal listeria outbreak</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/colo-farmers-arrested-fatal-listeria-outbreak-185524864.html"><img src="http://l3.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/xVyofCMss769wN_rWK9YnQ--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3B4b2ZmPTUwO3B5b2ZmPTA7cT04NTt3PTEzMA--/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/ap_webfeeds/20297b367cc686203e0f6a70670077cf.jpg" width="130" height="86" alt="Ryan Jensen, 33, front, and brother Eric Jensen, 37, leave the federal courthouse in Denver on Thursday, Sept. 26, 2013, after a hearing on federal charges of introducing adulterated food into interstate commerce. The brothers owned and operated Jensen Farms in southeast Colorado. They pleaded not guilty to charges stemming from a 2011 listeria epidemic that killed 33 people. (AP Photo/Ed Andrieski)" align="left" title="Ryan Jensen, 33, front, and brother Eric Jensen, 37, leave the federal courthouse in Denver on Thursday, Sept. 26, 2013, after a hearing on federal charges of introducing adulterated food into interstate commerce. The brothers owned and operated Jensen Farms in southeast Colorado. They pleaded not guilty to charges stemming from a 2011 listeria epidemic that killed 33 people. (AP Photo/Ed Andrieski)" border="0" /></a>DENVER (AP) — The owners of a Colorado cantaloupe farm were arrested Thursday on charges stemming from a 2011 listeria epidemic that killed 33 people in one of the nation&#039;s deadliest outbreaks of foodborne illness.</p><br clear="all"/>
